\begin_layout Title
Phenotypic integration of horizontal, vertical, epigenetic, genetic and
 environmental cues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Most analyses of the origins of cultural evolution focus on when and where
 social learning prevails over individual learning, overlooking the fact
 that there are other developmental inputs that influence phenotypic fit
 to the selective environment.
 This raises the question how the presence of other cue integration mechanisms
 affects the scope for social learning.
 Here, we present a model that considers the evolution of (i) social learning
 within the broader context of other evolving inputs on phenotype determination,
 including (ii) heritable epigenetic factors, (iii) acquisition of environmental
 information at a single point in time (phenotypic plasticity), (iv) dynamic
 updating of environmental information over time (individual learning),
 (v) phenotypic randomization (bet-hedging) and (vi) genetic cues.
 We consider a spatiotemporally fluctuating environment, allowing us to
 assess how fundamental properties like the rate of dispersal, the degree
 of environmental autocorrelation and local competition affect the evolution
 of each of these cue types (and combinations thereof).
 Thus, we extend analyses of the evolution and maintenance of social learning
 and culture by providing a general diagnosis of the conditions under which
 the full range of informative influences on development are likely to evolve
 and coexist.
\end_layout

