\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Social learning, the ability to acquire information from other individuals,
 is a fundamental requirement to cultural evolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Boyd1985,Henrich2003,Aoki2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, a substantial amount of theoretical work has sought to identify
 the ecological conditions in which selection favors social learning as
 opposed to individual learning (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Henrich2003,Aoki2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for reviews), finding that a mixture of both social and individual learning
 is expected to evolve in fluctuating environments (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rogers1988,Feldman1996,Aoki2005,Laland2004,Rendell2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, the conventional focus on the evolution of social versus individual
 learning overlooks that individuals can also obtain information about their
 environments by other means.
 For example, in spatially varying environments an individual's genotype
 can become statistically associated to its environment through local adaptation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kawecki2004,Savolainen2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, favoring the evolution of genetic cues on phenotypic development 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2006,Dall2015,Leimar2016,Leimar2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In environments that fluctuate predictably over time, theory predicts that
 individuals are selectively favored to rely on transgenerational cues that
 stem from their parent's phenotype or the parental environment (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuijper2015,Leimar2015,English2015,Kuijper2016,Proulx_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), transmitted through heritable DNA/histone modifications, parental hormones
 or even parent-offspring teaching 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Danchin2011,Radford2018,Boskovic2018,Groothuis2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Next, rather than relying on direct or indirect cues about the environment,
 individuals may also be selectively favored to rely on mechanisms that
 generate phenotypic variation instead (e.g., bet-hedging: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Seger1989,Starrfelt2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Consequently, the presence of other cues than social or individual learning
 raises the question how organisms should integrate multiple cues when adapting
 to different environments and how, in turn, this affects the evolutionary
 scope for social versus individual learning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While there are a large number of theoretical studies which have analysed
 the evolutionary implications of subsets of cues (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2006,Shea2011,Kuijper2014a,Tufto2015,Gestel2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), only a limited number of these studies have sought to predict how organisms
 should integrate a large number of available cues .
 These studies find that the rate of environmental change and the degree
 of environmental predictability are key parameters in determining which
 cue is most important in phenotype determination, while reliance on mixtures
 of multiple cues typically occurs in more restrictive settings.
 However, these studies have only focused on integration of individual and
 parental cues (e.g., genetic cues, bet-hedging, parental effects and individual
 learning [phenotypic plasticity]).
 By contrast, the potential to acquire information via different socially
 learned cues is yet to be considered in a context that tracks the joint
 evolution of multiple cues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand how the integration of multiple cues affects the evolution
 of different social learning mechanisms, we develop a model that tracks
 the evolution of alternative behavioural phenotypes in a spatiotemporally
 fluctuating environment.
 Organisms are selected to develop a behaviour that closely matches the
 local environment by evolving sensitivity to a range of different cues,
 where each of these cues potentially provides information about the local
 environment.
 Foremost, we consider that individuals can evolve sensitivity to socially
 learned cues about the phenotypes of others, who are either members of
 the parental generation (vertical social learning) or of the current generation
 (horizontal social learning).
 We then ask how vertical and horizontal social learning evolve jointly
 with other cues that may affect behavioral development, be it genetic cues,
 individually learned cues (here represented by within-generational phenotypic
 plasticity) and transgenerational cues on phenotype determination as in
 previous models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rivoire2014,Botero2015,McNamara2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover, because both horizontal and social learning can potentially involve
 different mechanisms with which models for social learning are chosen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Henrich2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the current model allows sensitivity to evolve based on prestige biases
 (where individuals obtain cues from the most successful individuals ) and/or
 conformity biases (where individuals obtain cues from the most commonly
 observed phenotope) for vertical and horizontal social learning separately.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Existing theory on the evolution of learning mechanisms (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aoki2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) often stresses the role of different costs in driving the evolution of
 social and individual learning.
 For example, social learning is typically thought to result in outdated
 information relative to individual learning, whereas individual learning
 is considered to take more effort (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rogers1988"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 more REFS).
 The key focus of the current model is different, however, as we want to
 assess what information different combinations of cues can provide and
 whether some cues can inherently provide more information over and above
 others.
 Consequently, we make no a priori assumptions about the relative costs
 and benefits of one type of cue versus the others, but rather have those
 costs emerge from the ecological scenarios (via migration and timing of
 life-history events) that impact the information content of the various
 cues.
 
\end_layout

