\begin_layout Subsection
Life cycle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Environmental variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An overview of the life cycle of the model is provided in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Each patch is either in one of two local environmental states (low 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, or high 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

), reflecting, for example, the local temperature or the amount of available
 resources.
 Patches can change environmental state independently from other patches
 at each time step: with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a patch retains its current environmental state during the next time step,
 whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

 it changes to the opposite environmental state.
 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leimar2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we assume that both environments change at identical rates, so the global
 equilibrium frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

 patches is 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathrm{high}}=1-f_{\mathrm{low}}=1/2$
\end_inset

, while the between-generation environmental autocorrelation of any patch
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\theta_{t},\theta_{t+1})=2p-1$
\end_inset

, so that when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 (rapid change), the autocorrelation is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 (no change), the autocorrelation is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5$
\end_inset

 (random change), the autocorrelation is 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Juvenile phenotype determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adults develop an adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq u_{\mathrm{ad}}\leq1$
\end_inset

), which affects their probability of adult survival 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 before reproduction in low and high environments respectively (see Figure
 1B).
 After adult survival selection, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 newborn offspring are produced to start the new generation.
 Each newborn offspring is produced by randomly selecting a mother and a
 father from among the surviving hermaphroditic adult breeders, potentially
 allowing for selfing in case the number of survivors is very small (this
 hardly ever happens
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We need to quantify this
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon birth, an individual offspring then determines its juvenile phenotype
 according to genetic, maternal environmental, maternal phenotypic and vertical
 social cues (see Figure 1A and eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:juvenile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 A juvenile phenotype is also affected by individual learning of the local
 environment (via juvenile environmental cues).
 However, dependent on the model in question, individual learning either
 occurs at birth or after migration (see results).
 Consequently, the juvenile phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 that is developed after individual learning is a logistic function of a
 weighted sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 of the various cues an individual has received.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{juv}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}\right)}\label{eq:liability:juvenile}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}} & =a_{\mathrm{g}}x_{\mathrm{gen}}+a_{\mathrm{\mathrm{ind}}}x_{\mathrm{juv,envt}}\nonumber \\
 & +m_{\mathrm{m}}x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}+m_{\mathrm{e}}x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}\nonumber \\
 & +v_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}+v_{c}x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}},\label{eq:xbar:juvenile}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where each of the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{g}}$
\end_inset

 (genetic cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{ind}}$
\end_inset

 (individual learning), 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 (maternal phenotypic cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{e}}$
\end_inset

 (maternal environmental cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 (vertical social learning; prestige bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (vertical social learning; conformity bias) reflects an unlinked and evolving
 diploid locus (bounded between [-10,10]) that reflects the level of sensitivity
 to each of the different cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 set out below.
 Note that horizontal social learning only occurs after birth and hence
 affects phenotypic development later in life (see eqns.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xbar:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Genetic cues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of the genetic cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{gen}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{gen}}=\sum_{i=0}^{n_{\mathrm{g}}}g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, it is the sum of the allelic values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{g}}=3$
\end_inset

 unlinked, diploid genetic cue loci 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Each allele can have values in the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq g_{i}\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 As has been previously shown , limited dispersal and strong selection can
 result in scenarios where alleles become associated with the local environment,
 so that they become informative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Individually learned cues (juvenile environmental cues)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Juveniles perform individual learning about the state of their local environment
 by observing a juvenile environmental cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{juv,\mathrm{envt}}}$
\end_inset

.
 To this end, each individual independently observes a binary cue reflecting
 the state of the local environment.
 The cue is equal to the actual environmental state (value 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, value 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

) with a probability given by the cue fidelity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\leq q_{\mathrm{juv}}\leq1$
\end_inset

, whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 an individual receives a cue associated with the opposite environmental
 state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Maternal cues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Juveniles receive two maternal cues: the first is a maternal phenotypic
 cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}=u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)-1/2$
\end_inset

 that reflects the value of the maternal phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 By subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)$
\end_inset

 we standardize the maternal phenotype between 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 so that the maternal phenotypic cue has the same range as other plastic
 cues (and hence evolved cue sensitivities can be directly compared).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-1)$
\end_inset

 is itself a function of her mother's phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}(t-2)$
\end_inset

 (a so-called cascading parental effect: 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kirkpatrick1989,McGlothlin2013,Kuijper2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), a maternal phenotypic cue can potentially give rise to grandmaternal
 effects.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Leimar2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an assessment of noise in maternal phenotypic cues, which we do not
 consider here for the sake of brevity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second maternal cue is a maternal environmental cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}$
\end_inset

, which reflects the value of the maternal environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rossiter1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as provided to the mother by the adult environmental cue (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The cue is equal to the actual environmental state (value 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, value 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

 in environment 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

) with a probability given by the cue fidelity parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5\leq q_{\mathrm{juv}}\leq1$
\end_inset

, whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-q_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 an individual receives a cue associated with the opposite environmental
 state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Vertical social learning: prestige biases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following previous models of prestige-based learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Henrich2004,Kobayashi2012a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we assume that individuals are able to evaluate and rank the performance
 of observed models.
 To this end, learners rank the potential survival payoffs 
\begin_inset Formula $S(u_{\mathrm{ad},i})$
\end_inset

 of each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in a random sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 adult models after survival selection has taken place in the previous generatio
n (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The potential survival payoff is evaluated based on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th model's adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad},i}$
\end_inset

 that is observed by the learner (see eq.
 [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] below) in the learner's environment at time of birth (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is then a function of the phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad},\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset

 of the sampled individual which has the highest ranked survivorship value,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}=u_{\mathrm{ad},\mathrm{max}}+\xi_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}-1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is a sample drawn from a Gaussian noise distribution with mean 0 and standard
 devation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

, and subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 standardizes the cue range to the same scale as for other cues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Vertical social learning: conformity-biases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow previous models of conformity-based social learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Eriksson2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where individuals evaluate phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 of each individual belonging to randomly chosen subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 surviving adult models from the parental generation in the local patch.
 Individuals take account of the number of individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}\leq n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 with a phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the low environment (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}<0.5$
\end_inset

), whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}=n_{\mathrm{c}}-n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the number of individuals with phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 We then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}} & =\begin{cases}
-1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}>n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{ (low-matching phenotype predominates)}\\
0 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}=n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (no phenotype predominates)}}\\
1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}<n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (high-matching phenotype predominates)}}
\end{cases}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we add noise to the cue by adding a random deviate from a Gaussian
 distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adult cue determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After juvenile cue determination, all adults from the previous generation
 die and individuals learn from other individuals of their current generation
 (horizontal social learning).
 Information acquired from horizontally learned social cues is then used
 by individuals to update the various cue weightings 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xbar:juvenile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and develop an adult phenotype.
 Consequently, the adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 that is developed after horizontal social learning is an updated logistic
 function of a weighted sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 of the various cues an individual has received.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}}\right)}\label{eq:liability:adult}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}+h_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}+h_{c}x_{\mathrm{horiz,conformity}},\label{eq:xbar:adult}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; prestige bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; conformity bias) again reflect unlinked and
 evolving diploid loci (bounded between [-10,10]) that reflect sensitivity
 to both horizontally learned social cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{horiz,}\text{conformity}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Horizontal social learning: prestige biases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Horizontally learning juveniles rely on the same mechanism as vertical social
 learning, where they rank the potential survival payoffs 
\begin_inset Formula $S(u_{\mathrm{juv},i})$
\end_inset

 of each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in a random sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 juvenile models (no survival selection has yet taken place; see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The potential survival payoff is evaluated based on 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th model's juvenile phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv},i}$
\end_inset

 that is observed by the juvenile learner (see eq.
 [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] below) in the learner's environment at time of birth (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The cue 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is then a function of the phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv},\mathrm{max}}$
\end_inset

 of the sampled individual which has the highest ranked survivorship value,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}=u_{\mathrm{juv},\mathrm{max}}+\xi_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}-1/2$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 is a sample drawn from a Gaussian noise distribution with mean 0 and standard
 devation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

, and subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2$
\end_inset

 standardizes the cue range to the same scale as for other cues.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Horizontal social learning: conformity-biases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We follow previous models of conformity-based social learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g.,"
key "Eriksson2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where individuals evaluate phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 of each individual belonging to randomly chosen subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 juvenile models from the current generation in the local patch.
 Individuals take account of the number of individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}\leq n_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 with a phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the low environment (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}<0.5$
\end_inset

), whereas 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}=n_{\mathrm{c}}-n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}$
\end_inset

 reflects the number of individuals with phenotypes 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}>0.5$
\end_inset

.
 We then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x_{\mathrm{horiz,conformity}} & =\begin{cases}
-1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}>n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{ (low-matching phenotype predominates)}\\
0 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}=n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (no phenotype predominates)}}\\
1/2 & n_{\mathrm{c,lo}}<n_{\mathrm{c,hi}}\text{\text{ (high-matching phenotype predominates)}}
\end{cases}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Moreover, we add noise to the cue by adding a random deviate from a Gaussian
 distribution with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{horiz,conformity}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

